trans-unit.source:
					In 1992, the United Nations Convention on Climate Change was adopted. The most important decision under this convention was the Kyoto protocal of 1997. Developed countries then agreed to reduce their emissions of carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, HFCs, PFCs, and sulphur hexafluoride by an overall 5% compared to 1990 levels by 2009-2012.

&nbsp;

Achieving the Kyoto Protocol target for greenhouse gas emissions for the EU and the Member States will require substantial further emission reductions, particularly in carbon dioxide emissions. However, energy and transport demands, and the associated carbon dioxide emissions, are likely to continue to increase. It is unlikely that current measures, including improvements of energy efficiency and increasing the share of renewable sources of energy, will achieve enough to offset these increases. Major policy changes will be needed beyond the Kyoto target dates if sustainable development is not to be seriously jeopardised by climate change.

